PrefacePreface'Go Green' a series of books on Environmental Education (EVS) is based on 
the EVS syllabus as prescribed by the N.C.E.R.T according to NEP and NCF.
To enable the studen ts to realize their holistic potential in the process of 
learning, we have laid emphasis on the major skills that are to be 
develo ped through EVS. These skills include environmental sensitivit y i.e. 
awar eness, activity, projects, discussio ns scientific skills  and .
For the develo pment of these skills the learners need to be awar e of their 
surroundin gs and becom e keen observer . They should have the spirit of 
enquir y, be able to express their views and exhibit creativity and 
originalit y in doing activities and projects.
Keepin g these needs of t oday's lear ners in mind we ha ve prepared this 
series of EVS books.
These books will also enable the teachers to develo p the skills in studen ts 
as well as assess their learning process.
Any suggestio ns for the betterment of the book shall be thankf ully 
acknowledged and incorporated in the subsequen t editio ns.

How Do Families Change W ith Time?
Chang e is a rule of life. The families we see today are not like the ones we found in 
earlier times.
Man y socio-ec onomic forces are changing the family structur e and quality of life in 
families today. People are adop ting new ways of life and are constantly trying to 
adap t themselv es to the changing environmen t. Let us under stand this with an 
example of Arun's house.The Changing FamiliesUnit–I : We And Our Family
1
SMARTTIPS SMARTTIPSDuring earlier times, extended families often lived under one roof. They were 
known joint families. The traditional family system is rarely found nowadays. 
The joint families are being replaced by smaller nuclear families. Let us look at 
the reasons for this chang e.(Knowledge )
Environmental Studies-5 06

Why Do P eople Move?
People may have man y reasons to move from one place to another . Some of them 
are–
! People living in villag es move to cities or towns in sear ch of better jobs.
! Impr oved life-style attracts people to bigger towns and cities.
! Some times people move to other countries for higher studies or better 
career prospects. This is called emigr ation. The people who migr ate to 
another country and settle there are called immigr ants for the new country.
! Natural calamities like earthquak es, floods, famines etc. force people to 
move to safer location.
! Some people have transferable jobs. They have to move to different places 
after a certain period of time. Their families also shift with them.
! Man-made calamities like terrorism and wars also force people to relocate.
! Adjus tmen t problem in a joint family set up force people to migr ate and live 
as nuclear families.One day, Arun was sitting with his grand mother and going through the family 
album. He noticed the pictur es of man y relatives whom we had never met. He 
asked his grandmother about those relatives. His grandmother told him that man y 
years ago, all of them lived together in a big house in Nainit al. Man y family 
member s moved out of Nainit al due  to various reasons and their joint family 
split ted into a number of nuclear families.
Challenges of Migration
Moving to a new place leads to several  problems.
! Adjus tmen t to new surroundings and new people takes a lot of time.
! The childr en have to chang e their school, which gives rise to adjus tmen t 
problem and affects their result.
! When the young er gener ation migr ates, the elder gener ation becomes 
lonely .
! The member s of the young er gener ation do not get love and care of their 
elder s.
! The progress of any place is affected when the young er and talen ted people

Changes in V alues And Beliefs
Migr ation not only chang es the structur e of a family but also affects the values and 
customs of a f amily . In earlier times , w omen w ere expect ed to stay at home and 
remain busy doing household work such as cooking , washing , cleaning , taking care 
of elder s and childr en etc.
In modern times, women have become educ ated and entered almos t all fields that 
were previously consider ed to be open only for men. Women are now doing well in 
engineering , law, politics, armed forces, sports, entertainmen t and so on.
With the changing time, man y customs and traditions have chang ed. Like, it was 
seen in olden days that ladies covered their faces in front of their father-in-la w. But 
today, fathers-in-law treat their daughters -in-law as their own daughters. 
Similarly , in earlier days all the import ant decisions were taken by the head of the 
family but now all import ant decisions are taken after the discussion and mutual 
consen t of family member s.
Today, women are managing the work outside the home too. So, men take an 
activ e part in various household activities to reduce the load of work at women. 
Childr en also help their parents in managing the house.
It was seen earlier that the son of a farmer became a farmer , the son of a tailor 
became a tailor but now this has chang ed. Now, the son of a farmer becomes an IAS 
officer or more. Now, people have become aware and do the work with their own 
will and interest.
Some values however remain unchang ed. The young er member s respect the 
elder s. Elder s also love and take care of the young ers.Advantages of Migration
Migr ation has man y positiv e effects also.
! It leads to better job and educ ational opportunities.
! It usually results in impr ovemen t of life style.
! It leads to cooper ation and mixing of cultur es.
In Mauritius , about 70% population are of Indian origin.You  Know Must (Knowledge )

Breathing Organs
Man y organs ar e involved in the pr ocess of br eathing. Out of them, lungs ar e the 
primar y organs. Your breath can both warm and cool an object. Whe ther the breath will cool 
or warm some thing depends on which of the two is hotter–the object or your 
breath. In cold weather, your breath is obviously warmer than your hands. 
But, compar ed to hot milk your breath is cooler .
We breathe all the time– while talking , walking , eating, sleeping etc. We 
breathe in oxygen and breathe out carbon dioxide.Let'sKnow Let'sKnowUnit–I : We And Our Family
Environmental Studies-5 12

Process of Breathing
Breathing is the process that help s our body to absorb oxygen and remo ve carbon 
dioxide from it. It involves two main processes. They are—Nose— We take in air through our nose. The two nostrils in our nose contain a 
sticky muc ous and tiny hair which clean this air by 
trapping the dust particles.
Trachea— It is also c alled wind pipe. It is a long tube 
that carries air into the lungs through a pair of thin 
tubes called bronchi.
Bronchi— These are two tubes that help air reach the 
pair of lungs.
Lungs— These are a pair of spongy bag-lik e organs 
located on either side of the breast bone in the ches t 
cavity. Our right lung is bigger than our left lung.
Diaphr agm— It is a strong muscle located just belo w the lungs. It help s to move the 
lungs up and down.
1. Inhala tion (Breathing in)—  When we breathe 
in, oxygen rich air enters our nose and goes to 
our lungs through the windpipe and bronchi. 
This process is called inhalation. While 
inhaling , the diaphr agm contracts to mak e 
more space for lungs. The lungs then enlar ge 
to take in more air.Inhalation
(Breathing in)Deep breathing is one of the best way to lower stress in the body. 
This is because when we breathe deeply, it sends a message to our 
brain to calm down and relax.You  Know Must (Knowledge )
Environmental Studies-513

2. Exhala tion (Breathing out)— After a short 
span of time of inhaling , we breathe carbon 
dioxide out of our lungs. This process is called 
exhalation. When we breathe out, the 
diaphragm relaxes and moves up and the 
carbon dioxide is pushed out of the lungs 
which is finally pushed out through the nose 
or mouth.
Breathing Rate
We do not breathe at a constant rate. Breathing rate keeps changing from time to 
time. When we run very fast or after a vigrous exercise, we breathe heavily and the 
breathing rate increases. Do you know why?
This is because when we exercise or run fast, the demand for oxygen to be brough t 
into the body becomes higher , and the need for carbon dioxide to be given out is 
equally high. The heart then starts pumping faster to circulate the oxygen through 
the body quick er and to get rid of carbon dioxide.Exhalation
(Breathing out)
My Breath— Hot/Cold and Humid
Sending a stream of air with force from mouth is called blowing. It is simply 
exhaling air . We use our br eath to mak e hot things c old and c old things hot. Le t's 
see some examples of our daily life.
! In winters, we blow on our palms to mak e 
them warm. This is because our body O
temper ature is 37C which is much higher 
than the temper ature outside. Thus, the 
air exhaled by our mouth is warm and 
mak es our palms warm.Blowing on palms
Environmental Studies-5 14

Chest Expansion During Breathing
As we breathe in, the diaphr agm contracts, the ribs and the ches t cavity expand 
allowing air to fill up the lungs. When we breathe out, the diaphr agm relaxes and 
the ches t cavity goes back to its normal size.
Protecting Lungs
Although tiny hair and muc ous in our nostrils trap mos t of the dirt, some times 
minut e particles of dust and smok e do manag e to reach our lungs and cause severe 
illness. Inhaling poisonous gases from vehicles and factories too can cause man y 
breathing problems. Diseases like asthma and bronchitis are increasing rapidly due 
to increasing level of harm ful gases in the air.
Though we can protect our lungs from the 
poisonous gases and dust particles by wearing 
mask s, it is not a solution. The real solution lies 
in working towards decr easing air pollution. 
Some ways by which the level of air pollution 
can be decr eased are—
! Reduce the number of trips you take in 
your car.! We blow on a glass of hot milk to mak e it cold. 
The air from our mouth which is 
compar atively cooler than the air around the 
glass, takes place of the hot air and lowers 
down the temper ature of the milk.
! During winters it is a common observation 
that the glass surfaces or mirr ors become 
cloudy when we blow on them. This is 
because our breath contains water vapour . 
After touching the cold surface, the water 
vapour condenses making it cloudy . The air 
containing water vapour is called humid air. 
Thus, our breath is humid.

Health
Health is defined as the state of comple te physical and men tal well-being of a 
person. This  means that both the body and the mind mus t be comple tely fit for a 
person to be health y.
To be health y we mus t–
! take balanced diet
! exercise regularly
! have proper rest
! main tain good hygiene
! protect ourselves from diseases
! main tain good postureGood health, as we all know, is very import ant. But do you know wha t we 
actually mean by 'health'?Let'sKnow Let'sKnow
Unit–I : We And Our Family

Balanced diet– We need food to live. Our food should have 
enough nutrien ts so that we grow and stay health y. The 
main nutrients include carbohydrates, fats, proteins, 
vitamins and miner als. In addition, our body also needs 
roughag e and plen ty of water. It is import ant to eat the right 
kind of food in the right quan tity. Eating too little or too 
much food can mak e us unhealth y. 
A diet that provides us all the nutrien ts in the right quan tity to remain health y and 
disease free is called a balanced diet.
Deficiency of nutrien ts in our food can lead to various diseases.
Prevention is always better than cure.You  Know Must (Knowledge )
Diseases
Disease is defined as the condition in which our body does not function properly . 
Diseases can occur due to man y reasons. They may occur due to deficiency of 
nutrien ts in the diet, eating contamina ted food or drinking contamina ted water 
etc.
Diseases can be divided into two categories–
! Communic able diseases
! Non-c ommunic able diseases
  Diseases which spread from one person to Communicable diseases– 
another are called communic able diseases. These diseases are caused by 
germs or micr obes. They can spread through contamina ted food, water, air, 
insect bites or direct or indir ect contact with an infected person.
 Examples of communic able diseases are–
 common cold, typhoid, dengue, malaria, measles, cholera, Covid-19, 
tuber culosis etc.
  The best method to prevent communic able diseases is to Prevention– 
main tain proper hygiene of body , food, water and surroundings.
  Some other methods are–
! Educating the people about the causes of such diseases.
! Proper vaccina tion, particularly during an epidemic.
